<div id="review_3925380395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3925380395" />
    <a title="Ushashi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/121021140-ushashi"><img alt="Ushashi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599845958p2/121021140.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3925380395?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ushashi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ushashi" href="/user/show/121021140-ushashi">Ushashi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121021140-ushashi?shelf=2021-reads">2021-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121021140-ushashi?shelf=nbrc-tt8-discworld">nbrc-tt8-discworld</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121021140-ushashi?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3925380395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10841812534992426076">Feminism is for Everybody demands what it says in the title and expects the idea of feminism to reach everyone irrespective of gender, class, education, etc. There are some parts in the book that I absolutely loved. Particularly the idea of going door to door to make people aware of the feminist movement. That could do some real good where misconceptions about this movement are so prevalent. Hooks also brought up some important but less talked about issues in relation to feminism, including abus</span>
  <span id="freeText10841812534992426076" style="display:none">Feminism is for Everybody demands what it says in the title and expects the idea of feminism to reach everyone irrespective of gender, class, education, etc. There are some parts in the book that I absolutely loved. Particularly the idea of going door to door to make people aware of the feminist movement. That could do some real good where misconceptions about this movement are so prevalent. Hooks also brought up some important but less talked about issues in relation to feminism, including abuse of children and spirituality. <br />What I felt to be the problem though was a) Hooks kept referring to her other books to the point that it started sounding like shameless self-promotion and b) the overuse of the phrase 'white supremacist capitalist patriarchy'. I understand that she believes it to be a problem, but using it so many times didn’t help. And this book is more of the insider critic of the movement, showing the shortcomings of the movements, often ranting against the ‘white educated upper-class feminists’ than making the idea accessible and acceptable to everyone, as it says in the introduction.<br />This is a brilliant book on feminism for those who already are feminists. It can give new perspectives and a better understanding of the first and second wave movements now that we are seeing the third wave and keep us from repeating the early mistakes. But it cannot act as a primer, which Hooks so rightly pointed out is much needed in the society. It fails to deliver on the promise it makes on the first few pages.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10841812534992426076" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


