  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3121622560" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3121622560" />
    <a title="Hope Martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24380480-hope-martin"><img alt="Hope Martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1539855163p2/24380480.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3121622560?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hope Martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hope Martin" href="/user/show/24380480-hope-martin">Hope Martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3121622560" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15223025446845179882">In her book, Hooks states, &quot;...we can work on behalf of feminism right where we are. We can begin to do the work on feminism at home, right where we live, educating ourselves and our loved ones&quot; (116). I love this idea and I believe this book is a step in the right direction I want to take, but it left me just wanting more. Perhaps I&apos;m missing something (I can&apos;t wait to discuss it with my book group), but I feel like those strategies to advocate for feminism were not as present as I would have l</span>
  <span id="freeText15223025446845179882" style="display:none">In her book, Hooks states, "...we can work on behalf of feminism right where we are. We can begin to do the work on feminism at home, right where we live, educating ourselves and our loved ones" (116). I love this idea and I believe this book is a step in the right direction I want to take, but it left me just wanting more. Perhaps I'm missing something (I can't wait to discuss it with my book group), but I feel like those strategies to advocate for feminism were not as present as I would have liked them to be. Instead, this book gives great background on the movement and provided me with minimal new information. My biggest takeaway actually had to do with racism (which I suppose as long as I'm learning that's fantastic). I do intend to read more of Bell Hooks' work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15223025446845179882" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

