  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3330611523" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3330611523" />
    <a title="Catarina Neves" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12189024-catarina-neves"><img alt="Catarina Neves" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641136981p2/12189024.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3330611523?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Catarina Neves" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Catarina Neves" href="/user/show/12189024-catarina-neves">Catarina Neves</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781317588368" href="/book/show/23369996-feminism-is-for-everybody">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12189024-catarina-neves?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12189024-catarina-neves?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12189024-catarina-neves?shelf=philosophy-and-society">philosophy-and-society</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12189024-catarina-neves?shelf=feminism-and-lgbtq">feminism-and-lgbtq</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12189024-catarina-neves?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3330611523" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16754034739101840625"><b>2021 Reading #0 (4/6) | <i>(<s>Belated</s>)</i> Black History Month &amp; Women&apos;s History Month</b><br/><i>(The perfect intersection of Black <s>and</s> Women&apos;s History.)</i><br/><br/><u>This book represents a lot of things for me</u>. The simplest: this was my first dabble into <i>eBooks</i> — which effectively showed me I hate <i>eBooks</i>, no matter how much I am enjoying them or their topic <i>(<s>just look at how long it took me to finish it: almost a year!</s>)</i>. The most meaningful and complex: this was also <b>my first few steps into intersectional feminism</b>.<br/><br/>The time I st</span>
  <span id="freeText16754034739101840625" style="display:none"><b>2021 Reading #0 (4/6) | <i>(<s>Belated</s>)</i> Black History Month &amp; Women's History Month</b><br /><i>(The perfect intersection of Black <s>and</s> Women's History.)</i><br /><br /><u>This book represents a lot of things for me</u>. The simplest: this was my first dabble into <i>eBooks</i> — which effectively showed me I hate <i>eBooks</i>, no matter how much I am enjoying them or their topic <i>(<s>just look at how long it took me to finish it: almost a year!</s>)</i>. The most meaningful and complex: this was also <b>my first few steps into intersectional feminism</b>.<br /><br />The time I started reading this book was... <u>interesting</u>, to say the least. I started it briefly before the <b>Black Lives Matter</b> movement gained momentum with George Floyd's murder, on May 25th 2020. I remember putting all my readings aside at the time and trying to emerge myself into readings that explained my privilege (and the ways I could use it for good) back to me. Wanting to be an ally was not enough anymore — especially coming from such a country with such an ever-present colonial past, in which the repercussions are still felt in the form of institutional racism. I need(ed) to do better. We all need(ed) to do better and understand the importance of allowing black people (and people of color, in general!) the platforms we, as a society, so often take away from them.<br /><br />Just like <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53826072.So_You_Want_to_Talk_About_Race" title="So You Want to Talk About Race by Ijeoma Oluo" rel="nofollow noopener">So You Want to Talk About Race</a> or <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40667455.Feminism_for_the_99__A_Manifesto" title="Feminism for the 99% A Manifesto by Cinzia Arruzza" rel="nofollow noopener">Feminism for the 99%: A Manifesto</a>, this book was not a particularly easy read — but if you liked the aforementioned, you will surely enjoy this one too. Focusing on the central premise of the book, <b>I learned that, unfortunately, feminism is not always for everybody</b>. It was revolting to realize that feminist discourse in academic and political spheres was/has been dominated by white middle-to-upper-class females, who very often disregarded the struggles of lower-class women and, consequently, women of color — unless the struggle also benefited them or their demands. It was revolting at best, and even more so as to understand that I have unconsciously contributed to the problem. The whole web surrounding the consequences of the Patriarchy in our society's most basic discourses also made me sick to my gut. <u>Gut-wrenching from beginning to end</u>.<br /><br />Twitching the words of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5863103.Angela_Y__Davis" title="Angela Y. Davis" rel="nofollow noopener">Angela Y. Davis</a>, I feel like <b>feminism is a constant learning (experience)</b>. After having identified as a radical and then liberal feminist, due to this book, I am now identifying myself as an intersectional/socialist feminist. Not entirely because of what I read here, but due to the enlightenment and guidance it provided. <b>Reading so many uncomfortable truths also helped me stop every once in a while to re-evaluate my actions</b> — which led me into an existential crisis about whether or not I actually am/was the activist I used to say I was — <b>and to read more into this type of feminism</b>. If you are looking for this kind of change, I can only 100% recommend it to you!<br /><br /><br /><b>
  <u>Side note</u>
</b>: Surprisingly, and without even noticing, I finished this book on the <b>
  <a href="https://www.un.org/en/observances/end-racism-day" rel="nofollow noopener">International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination</a>
</b>!<br /><br /><br /><i>[<s>Fka 2020 Reading #5 | Post-Quarantine</s> || Read between 11 May 2020 - 21 March 2021. | Review written on 12 April 2021.]</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="16754034739101840625" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


